                    <msContents>
                        <summary>An imitation of Ḥarīri's Maqāmāt by Abū Bakr ibn Muḥsin Bāʿbūd
                            called al-Maqāmāt al-Hindīyah (The Indian Assembles). </summary>
                        <msItem xml:id="manuscript_14013_item_1">
                            <title xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" key="">al-Maqāmāt al-Hindīyah</title>
                            <title xml:lang="ar" type="alt">المقامات الهندية</title>
                            <title xml:lang="en" type="alt">The Indian Assemblies</title>
                            <author key="person_42258040"><persName xml:lang="en">Bāʿbūd, Abū Bakr
                                    ibn Muḥsin, active 1715</persName><persName xml:lang="ar"
                                    >باعبود، أبو بكر بن محسن </persName></author>
                            <textLang mainLang="ar">Arabic</textLang>
                            <note><p>The work is mentioned in Sprenger's catalogue and described
                                    from a copy lithographed at Dihli in 1264 AH (1847 CE), but the
                                    author is there called Bāʿbūd (<quote>باعبود</quote>), while in
                                    the present manuscript he is clearly Bāghnūdi
                                        (<quote>الباغنودى</quote>).</p>
                                <p>On the flyleaves at the beginning and on the back are
                                    inscriptions which name the book as Maqāmāt Hindi, but the
                                    proper title is the one given above.</p>
                                <p>Each maqāmāh is called after an Indian city and begins <quote>روى
                                        الناصر بن فتاح قال</quote>.</p>
                                <p>The fiftieth maqāmāh is known as <quote>السيالكوتية</quote>, at
                                    the end of which is a short epilogue (folio 158a), with which
                                    the work ends.</p></note>

                        </msItem>
